                  <handDesc>

                    <p>Halantas. Final M (l27) is a simplified ma. Final T (l27) is a reduced ta with a short vertical tail instead of a headmark.</p>
                    <p>Original punctuation marks. </p>
                    <p>Other palaeographic observations. Anusvāra is normally above and to the right of the character to which it belongs. Long ī is hardly ever distinct (but occasionally it is, e.g. l8 kīrtteḥ); RM's edition silently reads the ī where appropriate, while my edition shows the short i used instead of long ī as a scribal mistake. Rare initial Au occurs in line 22, though it may have been written as O. RM reads it as Au and there is a faint curved stroke at the top right that, if genuine, distinguishes it from O.
